{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937113001/0480.xml":{"full_text":"The Weather\nFair, Cold Tonifht;\nFair, Warm, Wednesday\nFill Weather Report Page I\nHome Edition\nLate Sport News\n1:15 Stock Prices\nESTABLISHED 1881 VOL LV, NO. 282\nWATERBURY, CONNECTICUT, TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 30, 1937\nEIGHTEEN PAGES PRICE THREE CENTS\nJoseph F. Mulville New Secretary\nUnanimous Choice\nAt State Central\nCommittee Confab\nOpposition Disappeared After Members Realized Local\nDemocratic Body Had Things Well Planned;\nWm. J. Farley, New Britain, Treasurer\nPrestige of Waterbury\u2019s Democratic organization in\nstate party circles was higher today, following the\nunan&nous election last night of Joseph F. Mulville of this\ncity to the post of secretary of the Democratic State Central\nCommittee. As 69 members of the committee gathered at\nThe Elton, the expected fight failed to materialize when\nbackers of Representative T. Emmet Clarie of Killingly,\nthe local man\u2019s opponent for the election, declined to\npresent his name in the face of cer\ntain defeat.\nThe meeting brought about two\nnotable victories for State Chairman\nJ. Francis Smith of this city. Not\nonly waa his candidate, Mr. Mulville,\nelected unanimously, but his plan\nfor an advisory committee to the\nstate central committee, to consist\nof (me member from each county,\npassed without opposition. A battle\nagainst the plan had been predicted\nby members of the Suellacy-Oonnery\nfaction. Meantime, the* stock of the\nlocal party organisation, headed by\nTown Chairman John H. Crary, took\nan upward Jump.\nFarley Named Treasurer\nWilliam J. Farley, former state\nFWA administrator and a resident\nof N%w Britain, was elected party\ntreasurer, succeeding Fred B. Holt,\nof Hartford, who retired after serv\ning the party for 90 years.\nThe victory of Mr. Mulville was aU\nthe sweeter to his backers, who\nincluded State Chairman Smith,\nU. S. Senator Francis T. Maloney\nand National Committeeman David\nFitzgerald, of New Haven, because\nonly a few weeks ago their candi\ndate for national commltteewomen,\nMrs. Carleton Palmer, was beaten\nby Miss Mary Coughlin, who had\nthe backing ef \u201cOld Guard\". Mins\nCoughlin was victorious by one vote,\nwith Mw. Palmer's supporters, who\ndid not expect a serious battle, being\ncaught unprepared.\nMr. Mulville succeeds William M.\nGreene deputy motor vehicle eommh\n!art.^-^<1iaTXh r\nvents state employes from partici\npating lit politics. His name waa\npresented in nomination by Town\nChairman Crary.\nCrary Nominates Mulville\n1 see no need for oratory or\nlengthy speeches,\u201d said Mr. Crary. \u201cI\n(Continued on Page 4)\nSTATE HIGHWAYS\nAGAINJN COURT\nSubstituted Complaint Is\nFiled By Connecticut\nRural Roads Group\nHartford. Conn., Nov. 30\u2014(UP)\u2014\nA substituted complaint was filed\nIn superior court today by the Con\nnecticut Rural Roads Improvement\nassociation, pressing for an early\ndecision defining the authority of\nthe state highway and public works\ndepartments.\nIt was expected Judge John A.\nCornell would render a decision with\nin a. few days, permitting an appeal\nto the December, term of supreme\ncourt.\nThe substituted complaint was\nagreed upon at a conference between\nAttorney General Charles J. Mc\nLaughlin and Col. Ernest L. Averlll,\ncounsel for the association.\nJudge Cornell, in his decision on\na demurrer to the original complaint\nseveral weeks ago, held that the ao\ntlon was improperly before the court,\nbut ruled that Publlo Works Com\nmissioner Robert A. Hurley had no\nauthority over the highway depart\nment, headed by Commissioner John\nA. Macdonald.\n(Continued on Page 4)\nFRITZ KREISLER\nv WAS INTERRUPTED\nAnn Arbor. Mich., Nov. 30.-(UP)\n\u2014Frits Kreisler had to stop In the\nmiddle of his concert at Hill Audi\ntorium last night while more than 60\npeople beat a hasty exit. Someone\nhad discharged a fountain pen tear\ngas gun in the second row and the\nfirst three rows were cleared.\n\u201cIt must have been some little\nfreshman joke,\u201d Kreisler said later.\n\u201d1 have not been threatened, al\nthough I have plenty of enemies.\u201d\nKreisler resumed playing within\nfive minutes.\nGDiefyou know...\nthat stamp collector*\nmust have 34 design* for\na complete set of Chri*t>\nmas Seal*\nSTELLA O\u2019HARA\nSUIT SETTLED\nAward of $3,750 Is Made\nfor Cutler Street Crash\nin June 1936\nAnother chapter of the accident\ncaused by a driverless car belonging\nto a wealthy New Yorker closed\ntoday In superior court where Judge\nEdwin O. Dickerson approved a\nstipulated award of $3,760 damages\nto Stella O\u2019Hara. Thus, the legal\nphase of a collision on Cutler street,\nWatertown, June 38, 1086, In which\nthree persons were Injured when\na car without a driver rolled down\na driveway onto the main highway,\nended.\nThe suit settled today was for\n$15,000 and other suits brought by\nBertha Fasano, owner of the car\nIn which Stella O'Hara was riding,\nand James A. Fasano, the operator,\nhave been settled by the defendant,\nSydney Stephen Gilbert, of New\nYork, or his Insurer*\nConservator Named\nBut a conservator, laving E. Cole\nman, was appointed f\u00abr Stella O'\nntmoK\nbecause the plaintiff Is at Middle\ntown, a motion before the court\ndisclosed. The nature of her Illness,\nalleged to have resulted from Injur\nies In the accident more than a\nyear ago, may be permanent, It\nwas reported.\nThe Fasano car was proceeding\nalong\u2019 Cutler street. In a driveway\non a hill was the Gilbert car, the\ncomplaint read. The brakes were\nnot set, It was alleged, and the car\nrolled down the driveway onto the\nhighway, struck the Fasano car.\nThe driver, James Fasano, was\nthrown out onto a stone wall on\nthe property of Bartow L. Hemlng*\nway. The passengers In his car were\nseriously injured.\nMichael J. Galullo and Theodore\nV. Meyer were attorneys for the\nplaintiff, Walter W. Smyth, for the\ndefendant.\nARRANGED DUEL\nBECOMES MURDER\nBillings, Mont., Nov. 30-(UP>\u2014\nFrank Robldeau pleaded today that\nMike Hunts took him out on a\ncountry road for a duel, that Hunts\nbrought his wife and childr along\nbecause the winner was pledged to\nexterminate the other\u2019s family, and\nthat was why he killed him.\nHe said he.didn't kill Mrs. Hunts,\nbut that when her husband fell she\nsnatched up a gun and shot her\nself. Then the child, who Is only\nsix years old, attacked Robldeau to\navenge his dying parents, and the\nkiller had to beat him. \u2018\u2018Hunt said\nIt was my family or lhs,\u2019\u2019 the 66\nyear-old farmer said. \"I didn't want\nto kill them.\u201d The child lived to ac\ncuse Rabideau, who was oharged\nwith murder today.\nRobldeau said that the row was\n\"about some grain,\u201d and It was\nHunts who brought the families\nInto It, bent on destroying one or\nthe other In a feud akin to the\nCorsicans\u2019 vendettas out here In the\nwheat country.\nCORONER IS SENT\nSUICIDE LETTER\nNew York, Nov. 80-(UP)\u2014'The\ncoroner received a letter, which\nread:\n\u201cSir\u2014Please send to the above\naddress to get the body of the un\ndersigned, exit via gas route. Entry\nInto the apartment can be made\nvia the Arc escape as I will leave\nthat window unlatched. Kindly give\nInsctructlons to have the door locked\non leaving as prowlers have once\nbefore entered the apartment. A\nset of keys will be there on the\ntable.\n\u201cYours truly,\n\"ETELKA GERTEN BAKER.\"\nA policeman went to.the address\ndesignated, entered the apartment\nthrough the unlatched window, and\nfound Mies Baker dead. He locked\nthe door upon leaving.\nLOSES WEIGHT\nWhen Martha Raye was recalled\nto Paramount from a\npersonal ap\npearanpe tour to start work In \u201cThe\nBig ftoadcast of IMS,\" the first\nthing she did wees to weigh. She\nhad lost 18 pounds. She now weighs\nDemocratic Harmony Prevails As Mulville Is Elected\nThe Democrats State Central Committee elected a new secretary and treasurer last night at a meeting\nheld In the Hotel Elton. Joseph F. Mulvllle of this city was elected secretary; William Farley of New Britain,\ntreasurer. Seated at the table In the top photo are, left to right. Mrs. Nora Mahaney Harris of New Haven,\nvice-chairman of the Central Committee; Philip Hewes, executive secretary to Governor WHbur L. Cross who\nacted as temporary secretary at last night's session; State Chairman J. Francis Smith of Waterbary; and\nimm\nnight at the committee meeting, Secretary-elect Joseph F. Mulvllle, State Senator andAthlctlc Commissioner\nJoseph F. Lawlor, State Senator Edmund Gebhardt of New Haven, County Commissioner Matthew A. Daly\nof New Haven, and Democratic Town Committee Chairman John H. Crary, In front. _\nBoard Of Education\nHas Stormy Session\nIt Was Not Squabble Among Members of Board;\nParents Threatening Strike Over Croft-Clark\nSchool Caused It\u2014There Was No Strike\nLate News\nBulletins\nHUNTER SHOT\nEast Hampton, Conn.,\nNov. 30\u2014 (UP)\u2014Anthony\nLutcay, 15, while hunting\non his father\u2019s farm, wa's\nwounded critically in the\nhead today when he tripped\nover his rifle and the wea\npon discharged. The bul\nlet struck him in the fore\nhead, between the eyes. His\nSame was placed on the\nanger list at Middlesex\nhospital.\nROBBER TO DIE\nBay City, Mich., Nov. 80\n(UP) Federal Judge\nArthur J. Tuttle today sen\ntenced Anthony Chebator\nis, 89-year-old Detroit bank\nrobber, to be hanged at\nMilan, Mich., on July 8,\n1938, for the slaying of a\nbystander during an at\ntempted bank robbery.\nCOMMANDER DIES\nLos Angeles, Nov. 80\u2014\n(UP) Capt. Benjamin\nDutton, 56, commander of\nthe Cruiser Portland, died\nof a heart attack last night.\nLUDENDORFF IS\nSERIOUSLY ILL\nMunich, Germany, Nov. 30\u2014(UP)\n\u2014General Brio Ludendorff, the\nmaster military mind behind Ger\nmany's successes early in the\nWorld War was seriously 111 today.\nThe 73-year-old military leader\nwho faced death with Adolf Hitler\nduring the 1933 Munich putsch, has\nBuffered from a serious gall bladder\ncomplaint for some time.\nHe was reported dying last night\nbut today hospital authorities said\nhis condition had Improved.\nWhite noted for his bitter anti\nChristian principles, the agedgen\neral was\u2019under the care of the\ncatholic order, \"dieters of Mercy.\u201d\nThe verbal cannon* heard at yes\nterday\u2019* meeting of the board of\neducation echoed In the durance to\nday a* the threatened strike of pu\npils who were to be encouraged by\nparents, failed to materialise. Stu\ndents of the former Oroft-Clark\nschool reported this morning to\nDrlggs, Maloney, Walsh, Merrlman,\nBishop and Welton street schools,\nand many of those who failed to at\ntend classes yesterday as parents\nawaited the decision of the board,\nwere registered today In the build\nings to which they were transferred.\nIt was said that the absentee list of\nthese students today had shown a\ndecrease of about 75 per cent.\nSome Adjustments\nSuperintendent of Schools Dr.\nThomas J. Condon with whom the\nboard placed full power to make\nchanges In the list of transfers, said\nthat a few adjustments will be made\nas soon ns all of the children In\nvolved In the transfer have been ac\ncounted for. Those adjustments will\nbe made In consideration of the age\nand health of the students, not as\na rosult of the boisterous disapprov\nal of a largo group of petitioners\nwho appeared at the meeting and\nended the session abruptly with\nshouts of strikes, and threats to\nkeep the youngsters away from\nschool.\n(Continued on Page 4)\nCommandments\nWell Supported\nNew York. Nov. 30.\u2014(UP)\nThrough a student publication,\nundergraduates of New York\nUniversity voted their opinion\non the 10 commandments. The\nresult:\n1 am the Lord, thy God. thou\nshalt have no other god before\nme.\nFor, 1,104; against, 381.\nThou shalt not take the name\nof the Lord, thy God, In vain.\nFor, 1,303; against, 382.\nThou shalt keep holy the sab\nbath day.\nFor, 1,194: against, 291.\nThou shalt honor thy father\nand thy mother.\nFor. 1,473; against, 13.\nThou shalt not kill.\nFor, 1,484; against, 31.\nThou shalt not commit adul\nFor, 1,266; against, 319.\nThou shalt not steal.\nFor, 1,470; against, 15.\nThou shalt not bear false\nwitness against thy neighbor.\nFor, 1,443; against, 33.\nThou shalt not covet thy\nneighbor's wife.\nFor, 1,384; against, 201.\nThou shalt not covet thy\nneighbor's goods.\nFor, 1,450; against, 30.\nTOOK HIS LIFE\nHartford, Conn., Nov. 30\u2014(UP)\u2014\nJohn Titus, 25, awaiting Superior\nCourt trial on charges of theft and\nbeing a drug addict, committed\nsuicide by hanging last night at\ncounty Jail, Medical Examlnor\nHenry N. Costello said today. Titus'\nbody was found suspended by a\nbraided bed-sheet from a window\nbar.\nFEDERAL AID FOR\nSTATES MAY END,\nSAYS PRESIDENT\nProposals in His First\nMessage on Housing to\nBe Rapidly Pushed\nHOUSE, SENATE TO\nACCELERATE SPEED\nAlready Preliminary Work\nto Advance Plans of\nPresident Starts\nBY JOE ALEX MORRIS\n(United Frees Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, November 30.\n(UP) Congressional\nleaders opened the adminis\ntration\u2019s drive to put through\nits housing program today,\npreparing to call on public\nofficials, business leaders,\nand labor representatives foi\nadvice in the campaign to\nencourage business. A gen\neral speeding up of House and Sen\nate activities appeared likely as a\nresult of President Roosevelt\u2019s mes- j\nsage asking amendments to the\nFederal Housing Act.\nThe housing message and another i\npresidential message on curtailment:\nof public funds spent on highways. I\nwhich will be delivered to Congress\nat noon today, were the first formal\nmoves In tho President\u2019s program for!\ncongressional action to aid business\nand balance the budget.\nIn today\u2019s message Mr. Roosevelt\nasked Congress to reduce federal j\nhighway expenditures by $100,000,-;\n000 a year through amendments to\nthe existing highway act. He also\nwill ask that the amendments be\nenacted at the special session In\norder that the saving may be ef\nfected In the next fiscal year.\nSeveral Developments\nSeveral developments also Indi\ncated that everything possible would\nbe done to get action on the pro\nposed housing amendments during\nthe special session.\nThese developments Included:\nChairman Hgnry a. Steagall, D.,\n(Continued on Page 4)\nText of Highway\nMessage Sent In\nWashington, Nov. 30.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nfollowing is the test of President\nRoosevelt's special message to\ncongress on highway appropria\ntions:\nTo the Congress:\nBy the act of June 16, 1936 the\nCongress authorised appropria\ntions totaling $316,300,000, for each\nof the fiscal years 1930 and 1939,\nfor federal-aid highways, second\nary or feeder roads, elimination of\ngrade crossings, forest highways,\nroads and trails, and highways\nacross public lands, to be admin\nistered by the Department of\nAgriculture. This act also au\nthorised appropriations totaling\n$31,300,000, for each of the Hscal\nyears 1933 and 1939, for roads and\ntrails within national parks for\nparkways to give access to national\nparks and form (connecting sec\ntions of a national parkway plan,\nand for Indian reservation roads,\nto be administered by the Depart\nment of the Interior.\n$34,000,000 to Date\nUnder the first category there\nhas been appropriated to date on\naccount of the authorisations for\nthe fiscal year 1938 a total of\n$34,800,000 and under the second\ncategory a total of $13,800,000, or\na grand *total of $38,000,000 leav\ning $300,000,000 still to be appro\npriated for that fiscal year. To\nmeet obligations under this $300,\n000,000 of outstanding authorisa\ntions I propose to include an esti\nmate of appropriation of approxi\nmately $100,000,060 in the budget\nfor the fiscal year 1939, with the\nbalance to be provided for 1940.\nThis takes care of the authorisa\ntions for the fiscal year 1938 and\nleaves for consideration the au\nthorisations of $338,000,000 for the\nfiscal year 1939.\nPolicies Recommended\nIn view of tho large amounts\nwhich have been contributed by\ntho federal government, partic\nularly during the post five years,\n(Continued on Pago 4)\nJapan\u2019s Naval Forces\nSeize American Tug\nHaul Down Flag, Throw It Into River\u2014Italian Tugs\nAlso Suffer\u2014Both Nations to Make Vigorous\nProtests to Officials in Charge\nBY EDWARD W. BEATTIE\n(United Press Stall Correspondent)\nShanghai, Nov. 30 (U.P.)\nJapanese naval forces today seised\nthe American-owned steam tug Pel\ntung, hauled down Its American\nflag and threw It Into the Whang\npoo river.\nThey also seized tugs flying Ital\nian flags.\nIt was the first time the Japanese\nhad touched an American flag, al\nthough they had bombed points fly\ning that flag.\nThe American vessel was seised\nat the Klnleeyuan wharf In the\nFrench concession. The Japanese re\nmoved from the bridge house a sign\nIndicating Its American ownership,\nstruck members of the Chinese crew\nwith the sign and steamed down\nstream.\nStrong Protest\nIt was understood that United\nStotc Consul Oeneral C. E. Gauss\nregistered a strong protest with Jap\nanese authorities after which he\nmade a formal report to the state\ndepartment In Washington.\nIt was understood that the Ital\nian embassy also protested to the\nJapanese authorities who promised\nan Investigation.\nThe Japanese towed the Italian\nand American tugs past the United\nStates Cruiser Augusta and the\nItalian warship Monte Cuccolo with\nout Incident.\n(Continued on Page 4)\nLabor Groups Again In Deadlock\nPortland, Ore., Nov. 30\u2014 (U.P.)\nAmerican Federation of Labor lead*\nera Interrupted an attempt to aolve\nthe labor war In the clty'a lumber\ninduatry today, by demanding tho\n\"complete surrender\u201d of the Com\nmittee for Industrial Organisation\nat the price for peace.\nNegotiations reached a critical\nstage last night and Governor\nCharles H. Martin announced at a\nconference:\n\"We won't stand by and aee the\neconomic structure of our state\nruined. This fight almply cannot go\non any longer. It has got to stop.\u201d\nGathered at the meeting were\nfederal, state and city officials; civic\nleaders, clergymen, union spokes\nmen and employers. They were de\ntermined to end the strife that has\nleft 3,500 men Idle here for nearly\nfour months; Impoverished workers'\nfamilies; interrupted business and\ncaused a series of outbreaks.\nCharles W. Hope, regional direc\ntor for the National Labor Relations\nBoard, presided. He has certified\nthe C. 1. O. as collective bargaining\nagent for the sawmills, and the A.\nP. of L. has rejected his decision.\nThe A. P. of L. Is enforcing a boy\ncott against the mills, paralysing the\nln\u00bb\u00ab%**bome, secretary of the\nOregon State Federation of Labor,\nspoke for tho A. F. of L. unions.\n\"There Is no room In this country\nfor two major unions any more than\nthere Is for two governments,\" he\nE. B. O'Orady, state leader for 0.\nI. O. unions said:\n\"Tho A. F. of L. boycott Is the\nonly tiling preventing peace.\"\nMinisters spoke In pleading, con\nciliatory terms.\nOsborne said It was a 'fight to the\nfinish\", and would end only when 0.\nI. O. workers returned to the A. F.\nof L. lumber unions.\nThe trouble started when several\nhundred A. F. of L. sawmill workers\ntried to Join the O. I. O. The A. F.\nof L. called tho boycott and the\nmills had to close because A. F. of\nL. men refused to cut or haul lum\nber on railroads and ship*. Lumber\nproducers, carriers, woodworkers\nand all were affected by tho shut\ndowns.\nPeace Deadlocked\nWashington, Nov. 30 (U.P.)\nNegotiations for peace between the\nAmerican Federation of Labor and\nthe Committee for Industrial Or\nganisation were deadlocked again\ntoday less than 34 hours after thejr\nconferences had been resumed. Al\nthough federation ofleals booed\nHint the business recession would\nlorco the C. I. O. to adopt a con- j\ndilatory attitude, there waa no In\ndication from Chairman John L.\nLewie or hie lieutenants that their\nhopes would be realised. On the con\ntrary, Lewis exhorted workers to\nbund together In Industrial unions\nto light Increasing layoffs.\nThe new deadlock was precipi\ntated by the rejection of a partial\npeace proposal offered by the 10\nman C. I. O. conunlttee. The Fed\neration's three man negotiating\ncommittee decided that no agree\nment would lie acceptable unlew It\nembodied a final and full peace. The\nC. I. O. plan proposed:\nThat the Federation committee\nagree\u2014in writing\u2014to grant indus\ntrial union charters and concessions\nto the O. X. O. organisations In the\nmass production, maritime and cer\ntain minor Industries.\nThat in return the C. I. O. would\nagree to rejoin the Federation and\nwork out a schedule of harmony in\nother industries involving 30 C. 1.\nO. unions. However, the Lewis forces\nInsisted that their membership be\nformed into an autonomous depart\nment wihtln the A. F. of L. and\nthat the Federation's eonstltutlon\nbe amended to eliminate certain\npowers of the executive council.\nPANTHERS WAVER\nON \u2018ROSE BOWL\u2019\nPlayers Themselves May\nTake Back Vote\u2014But\nCollege Will Decide\nPittsburgh. Nov. 30\u2014\u2019(UP)\u2014Offi\ncials of the University of Pittsburgh\nsaid today \"that as the situation\nnow stands,\" the Pitt Panthers\nwould not accept a poslble Invita\ntion to the Rose Bowl or any other\npost-season game. The official\nstatement, which still leaves a loop\nhole for a decision either way. was\nmade after the Panther squad voted\nagainst continuance of the 1037\ngrid season, and then, In an unoffi\ncial caucus reportedly reconsidered\nand voted to approve a bowl game\nIf:\nPlayers are given \"pocket money\u201d\nfor the trip. Pocket money demands\nreportedly ranged between *180 and\n\u00bb3(g>.\nThe entire Panther squad Is tak\nen, not Just the 34 members of the\ntraveling squad.\nJames Hagan, director of Pitt\nathletics, said he had received a\nword of the reported second meet\ning, and that It was not called by\nschool officials.\n\"If the players voluntarily meet\nand reconsider their post-season\njame vote, the university will listen\nto their decision,\u201d the athletic di\nrector said.\nSKATERSONJA\nHENIE INJURED\nHollywood, Nov. 80. (UP)-SonJa\nHenle wu Buffering from a brain\nconcussion today a* a result of a\nfall while skating for a movie titled\n\"Happy Landing.\u201d\nOno of the Norwegian star\u2019s skates\nstuck on a piece of cotton while\nshe was executing a complicated i\nmaneuver. She fell backwards and\nwas unconscious for a few minutes, i\nMiss Henle still suffered dizzy\nspells today and work on the picture i\nwas delayed. The mishap occurred\nSaturday. Dr. William Branch said\nshe would return to work In a day\nor two.\nPROBABLY WILL DIB\nBoston. Nov. 10\u2014 (UP) Adalfo\nMattachlonl, M, of Worcester, who\nhas served 27 years of a life sen\ntence for murdering his brother,\nslashed his throat with a razor In\nhis sell at state prison today.\nWarden Francis 3. W. Lanagan\nsaid the prisoner \u201cprobatyy will\ndie.\u2019'\nSecond Message Calls for\nCancellation of More\nGifts From Gov\u2019t\nFUNDS FOR HIGHWAYS\nSHOULD BE CURTAILED\n$1,490,000,000 Has Been\nContributed for State\nRoads in Five Years\nBY JOE ALEX MORRIS\ni United Press Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, November 30.\n(UP) In his second\nmessage in two days, Presi\ndent Roosevelt asked Con\ngress today to curtail federal\nexpenditures on road build\ning drastically and thus help\nbalance next year\u2019s budget.\nHe recommended that Con\ngress in the present special\nsession spread obligations already\nIncurred over 1939 and 1M0, cancel\n1B3B federal aid to states, and limit\nfurther aid to not more than 9135,\n000,000 a year beginning In 1940.\nThe message was part of the ad\nministration's program to check the\nbusiness recession. It was offered\nas an earnest of its intention of bal\nancing the budget. The first mes\nsage, sent to congress yesterday,\nasked for revisions of the housing\nlaws, designed to start a boom In the\nconstruction Industry.\nThe two messages appeared likely\nto cause a general spending of\nHouse and Senate activities.\nSpeedy Action Necessary\nSpeedy action on his highway pro\nposals is necessary, the President\nsaid, because the highway act pro\nvides that gifts to states of $16,500,\n000 for the 1939 fiscal year are to be\nmade before January l, two days be\nfore the regular session of congress.\nPointing out that the federal gov\nernment has contributed $1,400,000,\n000 for highway purposes In the\npast five years, Mr. Roosevelt\nstressed the \u201cnecessity for taking\n(Continued SiTPage 4f\nFLOOD THREATS IN\nCONN. VANISHED\nThree Principal Rivers in\nState Have Begun to\nQo Down\n(By United Frew)\nThreats of terlous floods through\nout Connecticut were dissipated\nearly today when the Connecticut,\nNatchaug and Bhetucket rivers be\ngan levelling off after a contlnous\nrise of two days due to heavy week\nend storms.\nThe Connecticut reached a crest\nof 14.8 feet, or slightly lower than\nflood stage of 18 feet, at 8 a. m\u201e\nat Hartford. An appreciable drop\nwas anticipated during the day.\nNatchaug Recedes\nA recession also began in the\nNatchaug river at Wllllmantlc\nwhich rose to four feet, four Inches\nabove normal, and within five feet\nof the record made during the dis\nastrous floods of March 1938. Sev\neral sections of Wllllmantlo were\nInundated and last night 13 families\nwere driven from their homes. WPA\nworkmen threw up temporary earth\nen dikes to stem the river\u2019s rise.\nCrest At Normal\nAt Norwich the Bhetucket river\nreached r crest before serious dam\nage resulted. Merchants In the\nneighborhood of the river had been\nwarned to move their stocks from\nstorehouses and cellars. Many had\nJust received their Christmas mer\nchandise. The river, however, be\ngan to drop at 1:15 a. m.. when the\nuse of power pumps was dlscontlntte\ned.\nThe footbridge over the river\nbetween Taftvllle and Lisbon was\nwashed away.\nA sharp drop In the temperature\nover night heralded the end of the\nrain storms.\nTREASURY BALANCE\nWashington, Nov. *0\u2014(UP)\u2014Gov\nnrnnii'iit expenses and receipts tv.\ntin, current fiscal year through Nov\n271 h, compared with a year ago:\nThis Year Expenses l.nsf Yea,\n$2,068,866,836.75 82,856,972,016.11\nReceipts\n13,288,223,063.73 $1,630,262,824.41!\nDeficit\n$770,644,772,011 $1,236,719,266.6*\nflash Balance\n$3,815,726,187.68 $1,422,162,780.48\nS\nTELL THE\n\u2022UtL-OER\nTp OMIT THE\n\u00a9R*W|MG ROOM*\nWE H*VS HO\nARTI4TIM OUR\nfamu.v.'","height":"28332","width":"20500"}}
